[src:conda-package/anaconda-python-distribution] Co-founded in Austin, Texas in 2012 as Continuum Analytics by Peter Wang and Travis Oliphant, Anaconda Inc. operates from the United States and Europe.
[src:conda-package/anaconda-python-distribution] Anaconda Inc. developed Conda, a cross-platform, language-agnostic binary package manager.
[src:conda-package/anaconda-python-distribution] It also launched PyData community workshops and the Jupyter Cloud Notebook service (Wakari.io).
[src:conda-package/anaconda-python-distribution] In 2013, it received funding from DARPA.
[src:conda-package/anaconda-python-distribution] In 2015, the company had two million users including 200 of the Fortune 500 companies and raised $24 million in a Series A funding round led by General Catalyst and BuildGroup.
[src:conda-package/anaconda-python-distribution] Anaconda secured an additional $30 million in funding in 2021.
[src:conda-package/anaconda-python-distribution] Continuum Analytics rebranded as Anaconda in 2017.
[src:conda-package/anaconda-python-distribution] That year, it announced the release of Anaconda Enterprise 5, an integration with Microsoft Azure, and had over 13 million users by year's end.
[src:conda-package/anaconda-python-distribution] In 2022, the company released Anaconda Business, new integrations with Snowflake and others, and the open-source PyScript.
[src:conda-package/anaconda-python-distribution] It also acquired PythonAnywhere, while Anaconda's user base exceeded 30 million in 2022.
[src:conda-package/anaconda-python-distribution] In 2023, Anaconda released Python in Excel, a new integration with Microsoft Excel, and launched PyScript.com.
[src:conda-package/anaconda-python-distribution] The company made a series of investments in AI during 2024.
[src:conda-package/anaconda-python-distribution] That February, Anaconda partnered with IBM to import its repository of Python packages into Watsonx, IBM's generative AI platform.
[src:conda-package/anaconda-python-distribution] The same year, Anaconda joined IBM's AI Alliance and released an integration with Teradata and Lenovo.
[src:conda-package/anaconda-python-distribution] In 2024, Anaconda's user base reached 45 million users and Barry Libert was named company CEO, after serving on Anaconda's board of directors.
[src:conda-package/anaconda-python-distribution] He was succeeded as CEO in October 2025 by David DeSanto, who also became a company director.
[src:conda-package/anaconda-python-distribution] In May 2025, the company introduced the first unified AI platform for Open Source, Anaconda AI Platform, a central control for AI workflows that enables customization in Python-based enterprise AI development.
[src:conda-package/anaconda-python-distribution] That July, after reaching over $150 million in a Series C funding round, Anaconda was evaluated at about $1.5 billion.
[src:conda-package/anaconda-python-distribution] Conda was developed to address dependency conflicts native to the pip package manager, which would automatically install any dependent Python packages without checking for conflicts with previously installed packages (until its version 20.3, which later implemented consistent dependency resolution).
[src:conda-package/anaconda-python-distribution] The Conda package manager's historical differentiation analyzed and resolved these installation conflicts.
[src:conda-package/anaconda-python-distribution] Anaconda is a distribution of the Python programming language (and previously also R) for scientific computing (data science, machine learning applications, large-scale data processing, predictive analytics, etc.), that aims to simplify package management and deployment.
[src:conda-package/anaconda-python-distribution] Anaconda distribution includes data-science packages suitable for Windows, Linux, and macOS.
[src:conda-package/anaconda-python-distribution] Other company products include Anaconda Free, and subscription-based Starter, Business and Enterprise.
[src:conda-package/anaconda-python-distribution] Anaconda's business tier offers Package Security Manager.
[src:conda-package/anaconda-python-distribution] Package versions in Anaconda are managed by the package management system Conda, which was spun out as a separate open-source package as useful both independently and for applications other than Python.
[src:conda-package/anaconda-python-distribution] There is also a small, bootstrap version of Anaconda called **Miniconda**, which includes only Conda, Python, the packages they depend on, and a small number of other packages.
[src:conda-package/anaconda-python-distribution] Open source packages can be individually installed from the Anaconda repository, Anaconda Cloud (anaconda.org), or the user's own private repository or mirror, using the `**conda install**` command.
[src:conda-package/anaconda-python-distribution] Anaconda, Inc. compiles and builds the packages available in the Anaconda repository itself, and provides binaries for Windows 32/64 bit, Linux 64 bit and MacOS 64-bit (Intel, Apple Silicon).
[src:conda-package/anaconda-python-distribution] Anything available on PyPI may be installed into a Conda environment using pip, and Conda will keep track of what it has installed and what pip has installed.
[src:conda-package/anaconda-python-distribution] Custom packages can be made using the `**conda build**` command, and can be shared with others by uploading them to Anaconda Cloud, PyPI or other repositories.
[src:conda-package/anaconda-python-distribution] The default installation of Anaconda2 includes Python 2.7 and Anaconda3 includes Python 3.7.
[src:conda-package/anaconda-python-distribution] However, it is possible to create new environments that include any version of Python packaged with Conda.
[src:conda-package/anaconda-python-distribution] Anaconda Navigator is a desktop graphical user interface (GUI) included in Anaconda distribution that allows users to launch applications and manage Conda packages, environments and channels without using command-line commands.
[src:conda-package/anaconda-python-distribution] Navigator can search for packages on Anaconda Cloud or in a local Anaconda Repository, install them in an environment, run the packages and update them.
[src:conda-package/anaconda-python-distribution] It is available for Windows, macOS and Linux.
[src:conda-package/anaconda-python-distribution] Conda is an open source, cross-platform, language-agnostic package manager and environment management system that installs, runs, and updates packages and their dependencies.
[src:conda-package/anaconda-python-distribution] It was created for Python programs, but it can package and distribute software for any language, including multi-language projects.
[src:conda-package/anaconda-python-distribution] The Conda package and environment manager is included in all versions of Anaconda, Miniconda, and Anaconda Repository.
[src:conda-package/anaconda-python-distribution] Anaconda Cloud is a package management service by Anaconda where users can find, access, store and share public and private notebooks, environments, and Conda and PyPI packages.
[src:conda-package/anaconda-python-distribution] Cloud hosts useful Python packages, notebooks and environments for a wide variety of applications.
[src:conda-package/anaconda-python-distribution] Users do not need to log in or to have a Cloud account, to search for public packages, download and install them.
[src:conda-package/anaconda-python-distribution] Users can build new Conda packages using Conda-build and then use the Anaconda Client CLI to upload packages to Anaconda.org.
[src:conda-package/anaconda-python-distribution] Notebooks users can be aided with writing and debugging code with Anaconda's AI Assistant.
[src:conda-package/conda-package-manager] As a package manager, Conda allows users to install different versions of binary software packages and their required software dependencies appropriate for their computing platform from a software repository.
[src:conda-package/conda-package-manager] If there is no set of compatible dependencies, it will tell the user that the requested combination of software packages at the requested versions is not possible.
[src:conda-package/conda-package-manager] Secondly, Conda allows users to create such a set of software packages in isolation from the rest of the computing platform, in what Conda calls an *environment*.
[src:conda-package/conda-package-manager] This allows the user to create various sets of software packages for different projects.
[src:conda-package/conda-package-manager] When the users switches between those projects, they switch to the relevant environment, thereby avoiding the re-installation or removal of conflicting packages.
[src:conda-package/conda-package-manager] To further facilitate the setup of such environments, Conda can also install Python, the interpreter for the software packages itself.
[src:conda-package/conda-package-manager] Conda is written in the Python programming language, but can manage projects containing code written in any language, including multi-language projects.
[src:conda-package/conda-package-manager] Conda uses channels to obtain package metadata and versioning information.
[src:conda-package/conda-package-manager] For example, Anaconda distribution uses Anaconda repository containing over 7500 packages as the default (called *defaults*) channel.
[src:conda-package/conda-package-manager] Conda also supports custom channels that can be self-hosted.
[src:conda-package/environments] An environment is a directory that contains a specific collection of packages that you have installed.
[src:conda-package/environments] For example, you may have one environment with NumPy 1.7 and its dependencies, and another environment with NumPy 1.6 for legacy testing.
[src:conda-package/environments] If you change one environment, your other environments are not affected.
[src:conda-package/environments] You can easily activate or deactivate environments, which is how you switch between them.
[src:conda-package/environments] You can also share your environment with someone by giving them a copy of your `environment.yaml` file.
[src:conda-package/environments] For more information, see Managing environments.
[src:conda-package/environments] The directory where the conda distribution was installed into.
[src:conda-package/environments] This directory contains decompressed packages, ready to be linked in conda environments.
[src:conda-package/environments] Each package resides in a subdirectory corresponding to its canonical name.
[src:conda-package/environments] The system location for additional conda environments to be created.
[src:conda-package/environments] Other conda environments usually contain the same subdirectories as the default environment.
[src:conda-package/environments] A virtual environment is a tool that helps to keep dependencies required by different projects separate by creating isolated spaces for them that contain per-project dependencies for them.
[src:conda-package/environments] Users can create virtual environments using one of several tools such as Pipenv or Poetry, or a conda virtual environment.
[src:conda-package/environments] Pipenv and Poetry are based around Python's built-in venv library, whereas conda has its own notion of virtual environments that is lower-level (Python itself is a dependency provided in conda environments).
[src:conda-package/environments] There are potential benefits for choosing PyPI or conda.
[src:conda-package/environments] PyPI has one global namespace and distributed ownership of that namespace.
[src:conda-package/environments] Because of this, it is easier within PyPI to have single sources for a package directly from package maintainers.
[src:conda-package/environments] Conda has unlimited namespaces (channels) and distributed ownership of a given channel.
[src:conda-package/environments] As such, it is easier to ensure binary compatibility within a channel using conda.
[src:conda-package/getting-started] Conda is a powerful command line tool for package and environment management that runs on Windows, macOS, and Linux.
[src:conda-package/getting-started] This guide to getting started with conda goes over the basics of starting up and using conda to create environments and install packages.
[src:conda-package/getting-started] Anaconda Navigator is a graphical desktop application that enables you to use conda without having to run commands at the command line.
[src:conda-package/getting-started] See Getting started with Anaconda Navigator to learn more.
[src:conda-package/getting-started] To bootstrap a `conda` installation, use a minimal installer such as Miniconda or Miniforge.
[src:conda-package/getting-started] Conda is also included in the Anaconda Distribution.
[src:conda-package/getting-started] Miniconda and Anaconda Distribution come preconfigured to use the Anaconda Repository and installing/using packages from that repository is governed by the Anaconda Terms of Service, which means that it *might* require a commercial fee license.
[src:conda-package/getting-started] There are exceptions for individuals, universities and companies with fewer than 200 employees (as of September 2024).
[src:conda-package/getting-started] Please review the terms of service, Anaconda's most recent Update on Anaconda’s Terms of Service for Academia and Research, and the Anaconda Terms of Service FAQ to answer your questions.
[src:conda-package/getting-started] Conda is available on Windows, macOS, or Linux and can be used with any terminal application (or shell).
[src:conda-package/getting-started] Conda allows you to create separate environments, each containing their own files, packages, and package dependencies.
[src:conda-package/getting-started] The contents of each environment do not interact with each other.
[src:conda-package/getting-started] For more information on working with environments, see Managing environments.
[src:conda-package/getting-started] The active environment is the one with an asterisk (*).
[src:conda-package/getting-started] When the environment is deactivated, its name is no longer shown in your prompt, and the asterisk (*) returns to the default env.
[src:conda-package/getting-started] To verify, you can repeat the `conda info --envs` command.
[src:conda-package/getting-started] You can also install packages into a previously created environment.
[src:conda-package/getting-started] For more information on searching for and installing packages, see Managing packages.
[src:conda-package/getting-started] Channels are locations (on your own computer or elsewhere on the Internet) where packages are stored.
[src:conda-package/getting-started] By default, conda searches for packages in its default channels.
[src:conda-package/getting-started] You can also override the default channels in your *.condarc* file.
[src:conda-package/getting-started] For a direct example, see Channel locations (channels) or read the entire Using the .condarc conda configuration file.
[src:conda-package/getting-started] Find more packages and channels by searching Anaconda.org.
[src:conda-package/getting-started] If you get an error message `command not found: conda`, close and reopen your terminal window and verify that you are logged into the same user account that you used to install conda.
[src:conda-package/getting-started] Conda compares your version to the latest available version and then displays what is available to install.
[src:conda-package/getting-started] We recommend that you always keep conda updated to the latest version.
[src:conda-package/getting-started] For conda's official version support policy, see CEP 10.
[src:conda-package/package-manager] A **package manager**, or **package management system**, is software that supports installing, upgrading, configuring, and removing software for the host system in a consistent manner.
[src:conda-package/package-manager] A package manager deals with *packages*, distributions of software and data in archive files.
[src:conda-package/package-manager] Packages contain metadata, such as the software's name, description of its purpose, version number, vendor, checksum (usually a cryptographic hash function), and a list of dependencies necessary for the software to run properly.
[src:conda-package/package-manager] Upon installation, metadata is stored in a local package database.
[src:conda-package/package-manager] Package managers typically maintain a database of software dependencies and version information to prevent software mismatches and missing prerequisites.
[src:conda-package/package-manager] They work closely with software repositories, binary repository managers, and app stores.
[src:conda-package/package-manager] Package managers are designed to eliminate the need for manual installs and updates.
[src:conda-package/package-manager] This can be particularly useful for large enterprises whose operating systems (OSes) typically consist of hundreds or even tens of thousands of distinct packages.
[src:conda-package/package-manager] An early package manager was SMIT (and its backend install) from IBM AIX.
[src:conda-package/package-manager] SMIT was introduced with AIX 3.0 in 1989.
[src:conda-package/package-manager] Package managers like dpkg have existed as early as 1994.
[src:conda-package/package-manager] Early package managers, from around 1994, had no automatic dependency resolution but could already simplify the process of adding and removing software from a running system.
[src:conda-package/package-manager] By around 1995, beginning with CPAN, package managers began handling package repository downloads, and dependency resolution and installation as needed, making it easier to install, uninstall and update software.
[src:conda-package/package-manager] A software package is an archive file containing a computer program as well as necessary metadata for its deployment.
[src:conda-package/package-manager] The program may be in source code that has to be compiled and built first.
[src:conda-package/package-manager] Package metadata include the software's description, version number, and dependencies.
[src:conda-package/package-manager] Package managers are charged with the task of finding, installing, maintaining or uninstalling packages upon the user's command.
[src:conda-package/package-manager] Computer systems that rely on dynamic library linking, instead of static library linking, share executable libraries of machine instructions across packages and applications.
[src:conda-package/package-manager] In these systems, conflicting relationships between different packages requiring different versions of libraries results in a situation called *dependency hell*.
[src:conda-package/package-manager] On Microsoft Windows systems, this is also called *DLL hell* when working with dynamically-linked libraries.
[src:conda-package/package-manager] Modern package managers have mostly solved these problems by allowing parallel installation of multiple library versions (e.g.
[src:conda-package/package-manager] OPENSTEP's *Framework* system), a dependency of any kind (e.g.
[src:conda-package/package-manager] *slots* in Gentoo Portage), and even packages compiled with different compiler versions (e.g. dynamic libraries built by the Glasgow Haskell Compiler, where a stable ABI does not exist), in order to enable other packages to specify which version they are linked or installed against.
[src:conda-package/package-manager] System administrators may install and maintain software using tools other than package managers.
[src:conda-package/package-manager] For example, a local administrator may download unpackaged source code, compile it, and install it.
[src:conda-package/package-manager] This may cause the local system to fall out of synchronization with the package manager's database.
[src:conda-package/package-manager] The local administrator will be required to take additional measures, such as manually managing some dependencies or integrating the changes into the package manager.
[src:conda-package/package-manager] There are tools to ensure that locally-compiled packages are integrated with the package management.
[src:conda-package/package-manager] Upgrades of configuration files may be particularly troublesome.
[src:conda-package/package-manager] Since package managers, at least on Unix systems, originated as extensions of file archivers, they can usually only overwrite or retain configuration files, rather than apply rules to them.
[src:conda-package/package-manager] There are exceptions to this that usually apply to kernel configuration (which, if broken, will render the computer unusable after a restart).
[src:conda-package/package-manager] Problems can be caused if the configuration file format changes; for instance, if the old file does not explicitly disable new options that should be disabled.
[src:conda-package/package-manager] Some package managers, such as Debian's dpkg, allow configuration during installation.
[src:conda-package/package-manager] In other situations, packages are installed with the default configuration, which is then overwritten, for example in headless installations to a large number of computers.
[src:conda-package/package-manager] This kind of pre-configured installation is also supported by dpkg.
[src:conda-package/package-manager] To give users more control over the software they allow to be installed on their systems, and sometimes due to legal or convenience reasons on the distributors' side, packages are often downloaded from software repositories.
[src:conda-package/package-manager] Many package managers can be configured to never upgrade certain packages, or to upgrade them only when critical vulnerabilities or instabilities are found in the previous version, as defined by the packager of the software.
[src:conda-package/package-manager] This process is called *upgrade suppression*, or *version pinning*.
[src:conda-package/package-manager] Some of the more advanced package management features offer *cascading package removal*, in which all packages that depend on the target package and all packages that only it depends on are also removed.
[src:conda-package/package-manager] Although commands are specific to each package manager, they are translatable to a large extent, as most package managers offer similar functions.
[src:conda-package/package-manager] The Arch Linux wiki offers an extensive overview of commands.
[src:conda-package/package-manager] Linux distributions oriented to binary packages rely heavily on package management systems as their primary means of managing and maintaining software.
[src:conda-package/package-manager] Mobile operating systems such as Android (Linux-based) and iOS (Unix-based) rely almost exclusively on their respective vendors' app stores and thus use their own dedicated package management systems.
[src:conda-package/package-manager] A package manager is often called an *install manager*, which can lead to a confusion between package managers and installers.
[src:conda-package/package-manager] Most software configuration management systems treat building software and deploying software as separate, independent steps.
[src:conda-package/package-manager] A build automation utility typically takes human-readable source code files already on a computer, and automates the process of converting them into an executable package on the same or a remote computer.
[src:conda-package/package-manager] Later, a package manager typically running on another computer downloads the pre-built executable and installs it.
[src:conda-package/package-manager] A few tools, such as Maak and A-A-P, are designed to handle both building and deployment, and can be used as either build automation utilities, package managers, or both.
[src:conda-package/package-manager] App stores can also be considered application-level package managers (without the ability to install all levels of programs).
[src:conda-package/package-manager] Unlike traditional package managers, app stores are designed to enable payment for the software itself (instead of for software development), and may only offer monolithic packages with no dependencies or dependency resolution.
[src:conda-package/package-manager] They are usually limited in their management functionality, due to focusing on ease-of-use over power or emergence, and are common in commercial operating systems and smart devices.
[src:conda-package/package-manager] Package managers also often have only human-reviewed code.
[src:conda-package/package-manager] Many app stores, such as Google Play and Apple's App Store, mainly screen apps using automated tools only; malware can pass these tests by detecting when the app is being tested, and delaying malicious activity.
[src:conda-package/package-manager] There are exceptions: the npm package database, for instance, relies entirely on post-publication review of its code, while the Debian package database has an extensive human review process before any package goes into the main database.
[src:conda-package/package-manager] The XZ Utils backdoor used years of trust-building to insert a backdoor, which was nonetheless caught while in the testing database.
[src:conda-package/package-manager] Also known as binary repository manager, it is a software tool designed to optimize the download and storage of binary files, artifacts and packages used and produced in the software development process.
[src:conda-package/package-manager] These package managers aim to standardize the way enterprises treat all package types.
[src:conda-package/package-manager] They give users the ability to apply security and compliance metrics across all artifact types.
[src:conda-package/package-manager] Universal package managers have been referred to as being at the center of a DevOps toolchain.
[src:conda-package/package-manager] Each package manager relies on the format and metadata of the packages in its repository.
[src:conda-package/package-manager] That is, package managers need groups of files to be bundled along with appropriate metadata, such as dependencies.
[src:conda-package/package-manager] Often, a core set of utilities manages the basic installation from these packages and multiple package managers use these utilities to provide additional functionality.
[src:conda-package/package-manager] For example, yum relies on rpm as a backend.
[src:conda-package/package-manager] Yum extends the functionality of rpm by adding features such as simple configuration for maintaining a network of systems.
[src:conda-package/package-manager] As another example, the Synaptic Package Manager provides a graphical user interface by using the Advanced Packaging Tool (apt) library, which in turn relies on dpkg for core functionality.
[src:conda-package/package-manager] Alien is a program that converts between different Linux package formats, supporting conversion between Linux Standard Base (LSB) compliant .rpm packages, .deb, Stampede (.slp), Solaris (.pkg) and Slackware (.tgz, .txz, .tbz, .tlz) packages.
[src:conda-package/package-manager] For mobile operating systems, Google Play uses the Android application package (APK) package format while Microsoft Store uses the APPX and XAP formats.
[src:conda-package/package-manager] Both Google Play and Microsoft Store have eponymous package managers.
[src:conda-package/package-manager] By the nature of free and open-source software (FOSS), packages under similar and compatible licenses are available on a number of operating systems.
[src:conda-package/package-manager] These packages can be combined and distributed using configurable packaging systems to handle many permutations of software and manage version-specific dependencies and conflicts.
[src:conda-package/package-manager] Some managers of FOSS packages are released as FOSS themselves.
[src:conda-package/package-manager] The ability to continuously upgrade third-party software is typically added by adding the URL of the corresponding repository to the package management's configuration file.
[src:conda-package/package-manager] Besides system-level application managers, there are add-on package managers for operating systems with limited capabilities and for programming languages in which developers need the latest libraries.
[src:conda-package/package-manager] Unlike system-level package managers, application-level package managers focus on a small part of the software system.
[src:conda-package/package-manager] They typically reside within a directory tree that is not maintained by the system-level manager, such as c:\cygwin or /opt/sw.
[src:conda-package/package-manager] This may not be the case for managers that deal with programming libraries, leading to possible conflicts, as both managers may claim to own a file and may break upgrades.
[src:conda-package/package-manager] Ian Murdock commented that package management is "the single biggest advancement Linux has brought to the industry", that it blurs the boundaries between operating systems and applications, and that it makes it "easier to push new innovations [...] into the marketplace and [...] evolve the OS".
[src:conda-package/package-manager] There is also a conference for package manager developers known as PackagingCon.
[src:conda-package/package-manager] It was established in 2021 with the aim to understand different approaches to package management.
[src:conda-package/projects-conda] Conda provides package, dependency, and environment management for any language.
[src:conda-package/projects-conda] Here, you will find everything you need to get started using conda in your own projects.
[src:conda-package/projects-conda] Miniconda is an installer by Anaconda that comes preconfigured for use with the Anaconda Repository.
[src:conda-package/projects-conda] See the notes about Anaconda's Terms of Service.
[src:conda-package/projects-conda] Miniforge is an installer maintained by the conda-forge community that comes preconfigured for use with the conda-forge channel.
[src:conda-package/projects-conda] Want to get even more in-depth training on how to use conda for free?
[src:conda-package/projects-conda] Check out Anaconda's free course on conda basics.
[src:conda-package/projects-conda] Conda is an open source project and always welcomes new contributions.
[src:conda-package/projects-conda] Please read the following guides to get started developing conda and making your own contributions.
